            '<p>Two classic forms exist. <strong>Additive</strong>: Y(t) = T(t) + S(t) + C(t) + e(t), used when seasonal swings stay constant in size. <strong>Multiplicative</strong>: Y(t) = T(t) * S(t) * C(t) * e(t), used when swings scale with the level (e.g., AirPassengers: bigger summer peaks as the level grows).</p>',
            '<p>Identify the dominant components before choosing a model: strong seasonality pushes you toward SARIMA/Holt-Winters; pure trend suits Holt or ARIMA(0,1,0); a long cycle suggests business-cycle adjustment. Mis-identifying multiplicative as additive under-forecasts peaks.</p>'
