            title: 'Holt level/trend recursion with a worked example',
            code: `Holt's linear method:
  L(t) = alpha*Y(t) + (1-alpha)*(L(t-1) + b(t-1))
  b(t) = beta*(L(t) - L(t-1)) + (1-beta)*b(t-1)
  F(t+h) = L(t) + h*b(t)

Damped:  F(t+h) = L(t) + (sum_{i=1}^{h} phi^i) * b(t)

Symbols:
  alpha  level smoothing
  beta   trend smoothing
  L      level,  b  slope,  phi  damping (0,1)

Worked example, alpha=0.5, beta=0.5, L0=10, b0=1, y=[12,14,13]:
  L1 = 0.5*12 + 0.5*(10+1) = 11.5
  b1 = 0.5*(11.5-10) + 0.5*1 = 1.25
  L2 = 0.5*14 + 0.5*(11.5+1.25) = 13.375
  b2 = 0.5*(13.375-11.5) + 0.5*1.25 = 1.5625
  L3 = 0.5*13 + 0.5*(13.375+1.5625) = 13.97
  b3 = 0.5*(13.97-13.375) + 0.5*1.5625 = 1.06
  F(t+1) = 13.97 + 1*1.06 = 15.03
  F(t+3) = 13.97 + 3*1.06 = 17.15

Python:
  a,b=0.5,0.5; L,B=10.0,1.0
  for y in [12,14,13]:
      L_new = a*y+(1-a)*(L+B); B = b*(L_new-L)+(1-b)*B; L=L_new
  print("L:",round(L,2),"b:",round(B,2),"F1:",round(L+B,2),"F3:",round(L+3*B,2))`,
